_metadata.description: Individual Exponential Power Models for Each Configuration

power_model.description: Exponential power ramp model for GPU decode process

parameters.P_inf: Steady-state power (W) - final power when fully ramped up
parameters.delta_P: Initial power deficit (W) - how far below steady-state we start
parameters.tau: Time constant (s) - how fast we ramp up (63% in tau seconds)

power_model.physical_meaning: At t=0: P(0) = P_inf - delta_P (initial power), At t=infinity: P(infinity) = P_inf (steady-state power)

energy_model.description: Integrated energy from exponential power model
energy_model.usage: Energy = P_inf*T - delta_P*tau*(1 - exp(-T/tau)) where T = actual decode time from performance file

_metadata.structure: Top-level keys are actual model names from performance files (e.g., DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-14B)

data_fields.input_tokens: Number of input tokens in context
data_fields.r2: R-squared goodness of fit (higher is better)
data_fields.final_power: Calculated final power at end of sequence (W)
data_fields.decode_time: Actual decode time from performance file (s) - used for energy calculation
data_fields.monitoring_time: Total energy monitoring window duration (s) - used for power fitting
data_fields.tot_gpu_energy: Measured total GPU energy from data (J)
data_fields.decode_energy: Predicted decode energy from exponential model (J)
data_fields.e_total_less_e_decode: Difference between total measured and decode energy: e_total - e_decode (J)
data_fields.e_decode_vs_e_avg_diff: Difference between decode and average decode energy: (e_decode - e_avg)/e_avg * 100 (%)

limitations: Exponential model works best for sequences >64 output tokens
Very short sequences (<3 data points) cannot be fitted
Step-function power changes don't fit exponential assumptions
Hardware power limits: P_inf <= 65W, delta_P <= 60W for this system
Power fitting uses full monitoring window, but energy calculation uses actual decode time
